Fig. 2
 demonstrates the fluorescence emission spectra of the synthesised N-CNDs at wide-ranging of excitation wavelengths (λex). A gradual increase in the fluorescent intensity was observed in Fig. 2 (a) while increasing of λex from 280 to 320 nm. This could be traced to the fabricated carbon cores of graphite which shows π-π* transitions. But (Fig. 2 (b)) depicts the gradual decrease of fluorescent intensity due to n-π* transition while λex increased up to 400 nm. However, the maximum fluorescent emission intensity (λmax) of 405 nm was observed at 320 nm (λex). The calculated fluorescence quantum yield (QY) for N-CNDs was found to be 41%. The QY of the synthesized N-CNDs was quite higher than other reported CDs (Table 1
). This remarkable fluorescent nature of the N-CNDs was attributed to the non-uniformed size of CNDs and the various surface electronic states owing to the existence of carboxylic (COOH), hydroxyl (OH) and amine (NH2) functionalities over the N-CNDs surface [28,29]. These phenomena of N-CNDs enhance the utility of CNDs in sensing, bio-imaging and drug delivery applications [30].

The IR spectra (Fig. 5
                        ) of the B. flabellier extract (black line) illustrates the absorptions at 3432, 2928, 1706 and 1115 cm−1 which correspond to OH, CH, CO and COC (ether) functional groups, respectively and the IR spectra of the N-CNDs (red line
