                        ) showed IR absorptions at 3425, 2921, 1713, and 1112 cm−1 corresponding to OH/NH, CH, CO, and, COC functional groups, respectively. One of the bands observed at 1629 cm−1 correspond to CC str of the sp2 carbon presnt in the N-CNDs core [3,25,41]. The absorption bands at 3425 and 1460 cm−1 were due to the NH and CN stretching respectively which is the strong evident for the nitrogen doping on CNDs [42]. Thus, the FT-IR results revealed the existence of hydroxyl acidic, carbonyl and amine functionalities over the N-CNDs surface.

The reduction reaction of CR was observed using optical spectroscopy in the aquous medium at 25 °C. In UV spectrum of CR, the two absorption bands apeared at 498 and 350 nm respectivly due to π-π* and n-π* transition of the azo group [53]. The UV spectrum (Fig. 9
                         (a)) diplays the CR reduction by NaBH4 without synthesized N-CNDs. The intensity of CR was found to show a minimum decrease when measured at regular time intervals for 2 h. However, the synthesized N-CNDs (50 µL) was added to the reaction cuvette containing newly prepared CR and NaBH4 mixture, a considerable decrease was observed in the CR intensity (Fig. 9 (b)). Finally, the reduction of CR was completed within 10 min due to the addition of the synthesized green catalyst (N-CNDs). The above results confirmed that the incredible catalytic behaviour of the synthesized N-CNDs enhanced the rate of the CR reduction using NaBH4. This could be achevied by diminishing the activation energy of the reduction reaction due to the addition of N-CNDs [54]. The synthesized N-CNDs act as an proficient nanocatalyst in the CR reduction when compared to other reported nanocatalysts (Table 2
                        ).
